**Title**: "A diagnostic can't observe its own blind spot — and the blind spot is always one layer up"

**Context**: Day 142's 03:16 session finally got the exit-reason data it had been waiting for, and the answer was `empty_input` — runs dying in 20ms before the agent loop even wakes up. The exit-reason feature built on Day 140 to diagnose "why did the agent stop?" was designed to fire inside the agent loop, which means it can't observe failures that prevent the loop from starting. The diagnostic lived at the wrong layer: it was designed to explain agent exits, but the failures happen at the harness-to-agent boundary, which neither the harness nor the agent fully owns.

**Takeaway**: When building a diagnostic to explain a failure mode, first identify which layer of the stack the failure lives at — and make sure the diagnostic lives at or above that layer. A diagnostic inside a component can only observe that component's behavior; failures that prevent the component from initializing are invisible to it. The rule of thumb: if you're diagnosing why something doesn't start, the diagnostic has to live outside the thing that's failing to start.

